            <abstract>
                <p>According to <bibl>
                        <ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/>
                        <citedRange unit="page">20-21</citedRange>
                    </bibl>, at least three texts narrate the death of the Emperor Julian the
                    Apostate through the involvement of <persName ref="PRS7025Mercury"/>. Two of
                    these three texts are articulated in the form of mircales, known as cerculating
                    along <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7292MartyrMa"/>, <ref type="work"
                        corresp="LIT7293MartyrMb"/>, <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7294MartyrMc"/>, all  known to be assigned for <date ref="ethiocal:Hedar25">25th of Ḫǝdār</date>..
                    These miracles were translated in <bibl>
                        <ptr target="bm:Nollet1931Mercure"/>
                        <citedRange unit="page">22-24</citedRange>
                    </bibl> as the 'fist miracle' and 'second miracle'. This record is for the
                    'second miracle', here defined as Miracle of Mercureos: Death of the Emperor
                    Julian the Apostate (version b). This miracle is attested with (as in <ref
                        type="mss" corresp="BNFabb110"/>) or without (as in <ref type="mss"
                        corresp="BNFabb92"/>) <ref type="work" corresp="LIT7304TammeraJulian"/>.
                </p>
